<TopicInfo Title="Numerical Differentiation" Subtitle="Approximate f'(x) and f''(x) from function values">
    <p class="topic-info__overview">
        Numerical differentiation estimates derivatives using finite differences
        or polynomial differentiation. The step size $h$ controls the trade-off
        between truncation error and round-off error.
    </p>

    <div class="topic-info__cards">
        <div class="topic-info__card">
            <h3>Forward Difference</h3>
            <div class="topic-info__formula">$$f'(x) \approx \frac{f(x+h) - f(x)}{h}, \quad O(h)$$</div>
            <p>Uses function values at $x$ and $x+h$. First-order accuracy.
            Simple but asymmetric — error depends on the direction chosen.</p>
            <p class="topic-info__limitation">$O(h)$ truncation error; too small $h$ causes catastrophic cancellation.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="topic-info__card">
            <h3>Backward Difference</h3>
            <div class="topic-info__formula">$$f'(x) \approx \frac{f(x) - f(x-h)}{h}, \quad O(h)$$</div>
            <p>Mirror image of forward difference. Same $O(h)$ accuracy. Useful
            at right-hand boundaries where forward values are unavailable.</p>
            <p class="topic-info__limitation">Same limitations as forward difference.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="topic-info__card">
            <h3>Central Difference</h3>
            <div class="topic-info__formula">$$f'(x) \approx \frac{f(x+h) - f(x-h)}{2h}, \quad O(h^2)$$</div>
            <p>Uses symmetric points around $x$. Second-order accuracy — much
            more accurate than forward/backward for the same $h$.</p>
            <p class="topic-info__limitation">Requires function values on both sides; $O(h^2)$ still limited for very small $h$.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="topic-info__card">
            <h3>Lagrange Derivative</h3>
            <div class="topic-info__formula">$$f'(x^*) = P'(x^*), \quad P = \text{Lagrange interpolant}$$</div>
            <p>Differentiates the Lagrange interpolating polynomial symbolically and
            evaluates at $x^*$. More accurate for smooth functions over many nodes.</p>
            <p class="topic-info__limitation">Accuracy depends on node placement; Runge's phenomenon affects high-degree cases.</p>
        </div>
    </div>
</TopicInfo>